<!--
Rule 100201 — Registry Run Key Persistence with Suspicious Path or Script Interpreter
MITRE ATT&CK: T1547.001 (Registry Run Keys / Startup Folder), T1059 (Command and Scripting Interpreter)

This rule chains off Wazuh built-in rule 92302 (which detects command-line
Run key writes at level 6) and escalates to level 14 when the registry value
points to a suspicious location (\Temp\, \AppData\, \Users\Public\,
\ProgramData\, \Downloads\) or invokes a scripting interpreter directly
(powershell, cmd.exe, cscript, wscript, mshta, rundll32, regsvr32).

Note on backslashes: Wazuh's windows_eventchannel decoder escapes backslashes
once before storing eventdata fields, so the regex must match double backslashes
to detect Windows path separators. Each \\\\ in the pcre2 pattern matches \\
in the stored field. See README.md for the full discovery narrative.

Deploy: append inside the <group> wrapper in
/var/ossec/etc/rules/local_rules.xml on the manager, then restart wazuh-manager.
-->
<rule id="100201" level="14">
  <if_sid>92302</if_sid>
  <field name="win.eventdata.details" type="pcre2">(?i)(\\\\Temp\\\\|\\\\AppData\\\\|\\\\Users\\\\Public\\\\|\\\\ProgramData\\\\|\\\\Downloads\\\\|powershell|cmd\.exe|cscript|wscript|mshta|rundll32|regsvr32)</field>
  <description>High-confidence: Run Key persistence pointing to suspicious location or script interpreter (T1547.001 + T1059)</description>
  <mitre>
    <id>T1547.001</id>
    <id>T1059</id>
  </mitre>
  <group>persistence,attack,T1547,T1059,registry,defense_evasion,</group>
</rule>
